# 4. Supporting Code for the Abstract

The Abstract summarizes the problem, dataset, methodology, and four key
findings. Before writing it I verified each finding precisely so the summary
was accurate and specific rather than vague.

## 4.1 Key Finding 1 — Danceability Distribution

The Abstract references a concentration of danceability scores and a notable
spike in the distribution. I located the exact modal bin before writing
that claim.

```{r abstract-danceability}
dance      <- spotify_df$danceability[!is.na(spotify_df$danceability)]
breaks     <- seq(0, 1, by = 0.01)
bin_counts <- table(cut(dance, breaks = breaks, include.lowest = TRUE))
top_bins   <- sort(bin_counts, decreasing = TRUE)[1:5]

cat("Top 5 most common danceability bins:\n")
print(top_bins)
cat("\nMean danceability:", round(mean(dance), 3), "\n")
cat("Median danceability:", round(median(dance), 3), "\n")
```

## 4.2 Key Finding 2 — Energy Distribution

The Abstract describes energy as skewing toward high values. I confirmed
the exact proportions before including that claim.

```{r abstract-energy}
energy <- spotify_df$energy[!is.na(spotify_df$energy)]

cat("Mean energy:", round(mean(energy), 3), "\n")
cat("Median energy:", round(median(energy), 3), "\n")
cat("Tracks above 0.75 energy:", round(mean(energy > 0.75) * 100, 1), "%\n")
cat("Tracks below 0.25 energy:", round(mean(energy < 0.25) * 100, 1), "%\n")
```

## 4.3 Key Finding 3 — Energy and Loudness Relationship

The Abstract references a positive relationship between energy and loudness
as one of the paper's key findings. I confirmed the correlation value here.

```{r abstract-energy-loudness}
r_el <- cor(spotify_df$energy, spotify_df$loudness,
            use = "complete.obs", method = "pearson")

cat("Pearson correlation (energy vs. loudness): r =", round(r_el, 3), "\n")
cat("This is one of the four key findings summarized in the Abstract.\n")
```

## 4.4 Key Finding 4 — Strongest Feature Correlations

The Abstract summarizes the correlation findings. I verified the two most
notable values before writing about them.

```{r abstract-correlations}
numeric_feats <- c("danceability", "energy", "loudness", "speechiness",
                   "acousticness", "instrumentalness", "liveness",
                   "valence", "tempo")

numeric_feats <- numeric_feats[numeric_feats %in% names(spotify_df)]
corr_mat      <- cor(spotify_df[numeric_feats], use = "complete.obs")

cat("Strongest positive correlation — energy vs. loudness:",
    round(corr_mat["energy", "loudness"], 2), "\n")
cat("Strongest negative correlation — energy vs. acousticness:",
    round(corr_mat["energy", "acousticness"], 2), "\n")
```

