# 6. Supporting Visualization

I produced this visualization while preparing the Literature Review to
understand how energy and valence relate to one another. Eerola and
Vuoskoski (2011) describe these two features as the primary emotional
dimensions in music so I wanted to see what that looked like in our
specific dataset before writing about it.

```{r energy-valence-plot, fig.cap="Energy vs. valence — produced to inform Literature Review writing."}
ggplot(spotify_df, aes(x = energy, y = valence)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.15, size = 0.8, color = "#2E86AB") +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "#E84855", se = FALSE) +
  labs(
    title    = "Energy vs. Valence across all tracks",
    subtitle = "Produced while researching Eerola & Vuoskoski (2011) for the Literature Review",
    x        = "Energy (0–1)",
    y        = "Valence (0–1)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(face = "bold"))
```

**What this showed me:** Energy and valence have a weak positive relationship,
meaning higher energy tracks tend to be slightly more positive in mood but the
relationship is not strong. This was useful context when writing about Eerola
and Vuoskoski's claim that these are the two primary emotional dimensions —
our data shows they are relatively independent of each other, which actually
supports the idea that they capture different emotional qualities rather than
the same one.

