# 7. Sections I Wrote in the Team Paper

## 7.1 Abstract

This paper presents an exploratory data analysis of Spotify audio features
across 42,303 tracks spanning 15 music genres using the R programming
language. The dataset, sourced from the Spotify Web API via Kaggle, was
preprocessed to remove metadata columns and two physical outliers, resulting
in a clean analytical dataset with zero missing values across all 14 audio
features. Using ggplot2 for visualization and dplyr for data manipulation,
the analysis examined the distribution of danceability, energy, and tempo,
explored the relationship between energy and loudness, compared danceability
across the top 10 most represented genres, and assessed pairwise correlations
among all numeric audio features. Key findings include a concentration of
danceability scores near 0.78, a strong right skew in energy indicating
dominance of high-intensity tracks, and a bimodal tempo distribution
reflecting the distinct rhythmic conventions of hip-hop near 125 BPM and
techno near 150 BPM. A positive energy-loudness correlation of r = 0.60 was
confirmed, and genre was found to be a meaningful predictor of danceability.
The correlation matrix revealed that most audio features are largely
independent of one another, suggesting Spotify's feature set is well designed
to capture distinct musical dimensions. These findings demonstrate the value
of exploratory data analysis as a method for uncovering both statistical and
cultural patterns in large-scale music data.

---

## 7.2 Section 2 — Literature Review

Several prior works have explored music audio features, genre classification,
and mood-based recommendation using data-driven methods, providing important
context for the analysis conducted in this paper.

Schedl, Gómez, and Urbano (2014) provide a broad survey of music information
retrieval, noting that low-level audio features such as tempo, energy, and
spectral characteristics are foundational to automated genre and mood
classification systems [6]. Their work establishes that feature-based
approaches are effective but depend heavily on the quality and diversity of
training data, a limitation directly relevant to our genre-imbalanced dataset.

Tzanetakis and Cook (2002) were among the first to demonstrate that
computational audio features could automatically classify music into genres
with reasonable accuracy [7]. Their research showed that rhythm and timbral
features carried the most discriminative power, which aligns with this paper's
finding that tempo serves as a strong genre signal separating hip-hop from
techno communities at distinctly different BPM ranges.

Eerola and Vuoskoski (2011) examined the relationship between audio features
and perceived emotion, finding that valence and energy were the two dimensions
most strongly associated with emotional response in listeners [8]. This
supports the relevance of exploring these features in the context of genre and
mood-based analysis and reinforces why both were included as core variables
in this study.

Interiano et al. (2018) analyzed decades of Billboard chart data using Spotify
audio features and found measurable shifts in danceability, energy, and valence
over time, demonstrating that these features carry cultural meaning beyond
individual tracks [9]. Their longitudinal findings complement the
cross-sectional genre analysis performed here by showing that the same features
this paper examines have tracked meaningful changes in popular music over time.

Oramas et al. (2017) explored multimodal approaches to music recommendation,
combining audio features with metadata and user behavior [10]. Their work
highlights the limitation of relying on audio features alone and reinforces
the value of first understanding feature correlations — such as the
energy-loudness relationship identified in this paper — before incorporating
them into larger predictive systems.

