# 9. Reflection and Learning Outcomes

Working on the Abstract and Literature Review gave me a different experience
than teammates who were building code and visuals. My job was to understand
the full scope of the project well enough to summarize it accurately and
connect it to real academic work.

Writing the Abstract was harder than expected. It had to be written last
because it summarizes everything, which meant waiting until all other sections
were finalized before the numbers could be confirmed. Every sentence had to
earn its place since the word count was limited.

The Literature Review required genuine research. Finding papers that were
actually relevant to what our data showed — rather than just papers that
mentioned Spotify or music in general — took more time than expected. Running
the verification code first helped because it meant I could search for prior
work that connected to specific patterns we found, like the bimodal tempo or
the energy-loudness coupling, rather than searching too broadly.

If I were to extend this project I would want to expand the Literature Review
to include more recent work, particularly studies that apply machine learning
to Spotify audio features, since that is the natural next step beyond the
exploratory analysis this paper presents.

